The paper deals with the problem of computing a Nash equilibrium in a bimatrix game, which is a topic in game theory (cs.GT). The proposed approach involves investigating a hierarchy of bimatrix games based on the rank of the matrix A+B, which suggests a connection to linear algebra and matrix theory (cs.DS). The paper also mentions the use of polynomial time algorithms, which is a common theme in computational complexity (cs.CC) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the paper discusses the number of connected components in the set of Nash equilibria, which is a topic in graph theory and network analysis (cs.LG).
